Post title: Database - date field formatting
Post description: I'm working on a tracking sheet that learners update each time they complete a criterion. I chose Database because it can be exported by the learner. Trying to put a form together that has the following layout: Title of activity Category 1 Criterion 1 date1, (date2, date3) comment Criterion 2 date1, (date2, date3) comment Category 2 Criterion 1 date1 (date2, date3) comment Criterion 2... The issue is that the date field is auto-populated with current date each time the Database is opened. As only one date field is necessary for the evidence, if a learner completes it with one date, the rest of the dates will be automatically be put in my Moodle regardless, which is not correct for the purposes of evidencing. Is there a way to make the date fields be all blank to start with or to have placeholders? Also, is it possible to export as pdf? That would be more suitable for exam bodies as evidence.
Comments associated with the post: 
Comment 1: As far as I know, there is no way to make the Date Field blank in Moodle Database Activity. One other way you might consider doing it is to have each entry contain just ONE Date, and then make a Radio Button or a Menu Field for the Category. Each user would just add a new record when they complete the step which would contain the date they completed that step. If you get clever with Groups (one user per group and separate groups), you can display each user's entries in the "List view" to see how many steps they have completed. Or you use the "Approval required" setting, and don't approve any entries to keep them "private" for students. You would need to filter by Student in order to see only one student's entries. You can use JavaScript in your template to "print" list views which would download as a PDF depending on your browser settings. There is a webinar and Moodle Academy course coming up in September on Moodle Database which may give you more ideas.
Comment 2: I have encountered similar problems with the database activity. One possible solution, would be to set the date field up using a text field, rather than a date field. This isn't quite as attractive as you don't get the 'date picker' options, and you cannot do anything with the dates - e.g. sort by date (as people will enter them in all sorts of different formats), but it does overcome the issue of the field being populated when you don't want it to be.
Comment 3: Hi, to be flexible, I wouldn't use the date field type but rather a number field (for timestamps) or a short text field, that i used here. In the "Add entry template" I changed the input html into this: 
```text
<div class="mb-3 pt-3">
  <div class="fw-bold">Date</div>
  <div class="date-field">
date
</div>
</div>

[...]

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/flatpickr"></script>
<script>
window.document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", (event) => {
  // Add the flatpickr stylesheet if it is not already there.
  if(!document.getElementById('flatpickr_css')) {
    var link = document.createElement('link');
    link.id = 'flatpickr_css';
    link.rel = 'stylesheet';
    link.href = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/flatpickr/dist/flatpickr.min.
css
';
    document.head.appendChild(link);
  }
  flatpickr('.date-field input');
});
</script>
```
 so basically adding a div with a class around my date field placeholder. At the end of the existing code in the template, the javascript is added. The input field can be easily set via a datepicker provided by the flatpickr.js library now. I am not sure whether the link element can be in the body at any place, therefore I add the css stylesheet via javascript in the header. The stored values are in the form of YYYY-MM-DD. These dates can actually be sorted. If in the output you want a custom formatted date, you can do something like this e.g. in the Single View template: 
```text
<div class="mt-4">
  <span class="fw-bold">date</span>
  <p class="mt-2 date-field-out">
date
</p>
</div>

[...]

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/dayjs@1/dayjs.min.js"></script>
<script>
window.document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', (event) => {
  const nodes = document.querySelectorAll('.date-field-out');
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    const value = nodes[i].innerHTML;
    if (value.trim().length > 0) {
      dayjs(value).format('MMMM D, YYYY');
    }
  }
});
</script>
```
 Again, in the existing html, the p element is extended by the class "date-field-out". The javascript loads the day.js library, reads the YYYY-MM-DD date contents and reformats them to the given format. One thing to watch out when using dates, is the timezone and daylight savings time. For this PoC I didn't check any of these issues, but you should be aware of it and may change the code a bit. The mentioned libraries support this, while the plain Date object within javascript treats everything as UTC. HTH , Stephan PS. the square brackets in the code are lost, so whenever the date appears as a link, it's the placeholder with the square brackets. PPS. to have the output of a list view or single view printed as a PDF, you could do something similar that I have done in https://github.com/srobotta/moodle-database-presets/tree/master/personel-list
