Post title: Embed pdf in single view
Post description: Hello! I'm building a database for how-to documents. I created these how-to documents with an external program (Scribe how) that allowed me to create them quite quickly. I decided to export them as PDF so we don't have to pay for the tool indefinitely. The idea would be to embed the PDF file in the single view, instead of users having to download the file or open it in a new tab. Any idea on how to achieve that? Thanks in advance for any help you could provide! Lucie
Comments associated with the post: 
Comment 1: I assume that you have a field set with one field of type file. In my case I named the file type field "pdf". Having this prerequisites in your "Single view template at the bottom you could add the following: 
```text
<script>
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
    const a = document.querySelector("#defaulttemplate-single a.data-field-link");
    if (a) {
      const href = a.getAttribute('href');
      if (href && href.substr(-4).toLowerCase() === '.pdf' ) {
        const embed = document.createElement('embed');
        embed.setAttribute('width', '500');
        embed.setAttribute('height', '375');
        embed.setAttribute('src', href);
        embed.setAttribute('type', 'application/pdf');
        a.replaceWith(embed);
      }
    }
});
</script>
```
 The rest of the template remains unchanged. In the template the file is inserted dynamically with the placeholer pdf . That creates a link and an icon in front of it (to illustrate the filetype). This javascript snippet checks for the link, actually checks that there is a pdf linked (only by looking at the suffix of the file). In that case the anchor element is replaced by: 
```text
<embed src="https://url.to.your.moodle/the.pdf" width="500" height="375"  type="application/pdf">
```
 Unfortunately you cannot limit the file upload to a pdf ( AFAIK ) and (just checked) you can fool Moodle by renaming an image to pdf which then brings you a blank embed window. There is no mimetype check when the placeholder is replaced by the icon and link.
Comment 2: Hello Stephan, thank you very much for your reply! Unfortunately, I think I'm missing something... When I add your code, it doesn't display the PDF in an embedded frame on the single-view page, but it opens it in a new tab. I tried adding the code at the end of my single view template or in the custom JavaScript template, but I have the same result... Here is how my single view template looks like with your code: `<div>` `<div>` `<p style="text-align: right;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">‚¨ÜÔ∏è </span><em` `style="font-size: 10pt;">Select "list view" to go back to the how-to` `general list.</em></p>` `<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 44.5938px;"`
Comment 3: Hi, In your template you have the Javascript included twice, remove one block. Also, remove the p element around the script tags. I always recommend to disable the code editor (uncheck the box) to have a plain text area for the template editing. Then you get the plain HTML and avoid errors when the editor does things (e.g. enclosing each paragraph into a p element) that are not preferred. What I also spot in your code is the missing id that is there by default and used in the javascript snippet. I guess your double square "How to pdf" is the variable placeholder that produces the link. In this case in your div element with the font-size or any other element, that contains the link to the pdf, add the id="defaulttemplate-single" attribute. The other solution would be going without the id attribute. In this case change the selector in the code from 
```text



¬† "#defaulttemplate-single a.data-field-link"
```
 to `"a.data-field-link"` I used the id selector to replace only links inside that template and avoid unwanted replacements of any other links that might be on the page (although unlikely). If that still doesn't help then open the javascript console to see if there are any other errors that keep the Javascript from working correctly. Best regards, Stephan
